\title{Content Research Writer}

\taxon{skill}

\meta{description}{Assists in writing high-quality content by conducting research, adding}

\subtree{
\title{Content Research Writer}
\p{This skill acts as your writing partner, helping you research, outline, draft, and refine content while maintaining your unique voice and style.}

\subtree{
\title{When to Use This Skill}
\ul{
\li{Writing blog posts, articles, or newsletters}
\li{Creating educational content or tutorials}
\li{Drafting thought leadership pieces}
\li{Researching and writing case studies}
\li{Producing technical documentation with sources}
\li{Writing with proper citations and references}
\li{Improving hooks and introductions}
\li{Getting section-by-section feedback while writing}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{What This Skill Does}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Collaborative Outlining}: Helps you structure ideas into coherent outlines}
\li{\strong{Research Assistance}: Finds relevant information and adds citations}
\li{\strong{Hook Improvement}: Strengthens your opening to capture attention}
\li{\strong{Section Feedback}: Reviews each section as you write}
\li{\strong{Voice Preservation}: Maintains your writing style and tone}
\li{\strong{Citation Management}: Adds and formats references properly}
\li{\strong{Iterative Refinement}: Helps you improve through multiple drafts}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{How to Use}
\subtree{
\title{Setup Your Writing Environment}
\p{Create a dedicated folder for your article:}

\pre{\startverb
mkdir ~/writing/my-article-title
cd ~/writing/my-article-title
\stopverb}

\p{Create your draft file:}

\pre{\startverb
touch article-draft.md
\stopverb}

\p{Open Claude Code from this directory and start writing.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Basic Workflow}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Start with an outline}:}
}

\pre{\startverb
Help me create an outline for an article about [topic]
\stopverb}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Research and add citations}:}
}

\pre{\startverb
Research [specific topic] and add citations to my outline
\stopverb}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Improve the hook}:}
}

\pre{\startverb
Here's my introduction. Help me make the hook more compelling.
\stopverb}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Get section feedback}:}
}

\pre{\startverb
I just finished the "Why This Matters" section. Review it and give feedback.
\stopverb}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Refine and polish}:}
}

\pre{\startverb
Review the full draft for flow, clarity, and consistency.
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Instructions}
\p{When a user requests writing assistance:}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Understand the Writing Project}}
\li{What's the topic and main argument?}
\li{Who's the target audience?}
\li{What's the desired length/format?}
\li{What's your goal? (educate, persuade, entertain, explain)}
\li{Any existing research or sources to include?}
\li{What's your writing style? (formal, conversational, technical)}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Collaborative Outlining}}
\li{[Opening line/story/statistic]}
\li{[Why reader should care]}
\li{Context and background}
\li{Problem statement}
\li{What this article covers}
\li{Key point A}
\li{Key point B}
\li{Example/evidence}
\li{[Research needed: specific topic]}
\li{Key point C}
\li{Key point D}
\li{Data/citation needed}
\li{Key point E}
\li{Counter-arguments}
\li{Resolution}
\li{Summary of main points}
\li{Call to action}
\li{Final thought}
\li{[ ] Find data on [topic]}
\li{[ ] Get examples of [concept]}
\li{[ ] Source citation for [claim]}
\li{Adjust based on feedback}
\li{Ensure logical flow}
\li{Identify research gaps}
\li{Mark sections for deep dives}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Conduct Research}}
\li{Search for relevant information}
\li{Find credible sources}
\li{Extract key facts, quotes, and data}
\li{Add citations in requested format}
\li{\startverb **Productivity Gains**: Studies show 40% time savings for \stopverb}
\li{\startverb **Adoption Rates**: 67% of knowledge workers use AI tools \stopverb}
\li{\strong{Expert Quote}: "AI augments rather than replaces human }
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Improve Hooks}}
\li{What works: [positive elements]}
\li{What could be stronger: [areas for improvement]}
\li{Emotional impact: [current vs. potential]}
\li{Does it create curiosity?}
\li{Does it promise value?}
\li{Is it specific enough?}
\li{Does it match the audience?}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Provide Section-by-Section Feedback}}
\li{[Strength 1]}
\li{[Strength 2]}
\li{[Strength 3]}
\li{[Specific issue] → [Suggested fix]}
\li{[Complex sentence] → [Simpler alternative]}
\li{[Transition issue] → [Better connection]}
\li{[Paragraph order] → [Suggested reordering]}
\li{[Claim needing support] → [Add citation or example]}
\li{[Generic statement] → [Make more specific]}
\li{[Tone inconsistency] → [Match your voice better]}
\li{[Word choice] → [Stronger alternative]}
\li{[Thought-provoking question 1]}
\li{[Thought-provoking question 2]}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Preserve Writer's Voice}}
\li{\strong{Learn their style}: Read existing writing samples}
\li{\strong{Suggest, don't replace}: Offer options, not directives}
\li{\strong{Match tone}: Formal, casual, technical, friendly}
\li{\strong{Respect choices}: If they prefer their version, support it}
\li{\strong{Enhance, don't override}: Make their writing better, not different}
\li{"Does this sound like you?"}
\li{"Is this the right tone?"}
\li{"Should I be more/less [formal/casual/technical]?"}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Citation Management}}
\li{Author. (Year). "Title". Publication.}
\li{Author. (Year). "Title". Publication.}
}

\ol{
\li{\strong{Final Review and Polish}}
\li{[Major strength 1]}
\li{[Major strength 2]}
\li{[Major strength 3]}
\li{[Comments on organization]}
\li{[Transition quality]}
\li{[Pacing assessment]}
\li{[Argument strength]}
\li{[Evidence sufficiency]}
\li{[Example effectiveness]}
\li{Grammar and mechanics: [assessment]}
\li{Consistency: [assessment]}
\li{Citations: [completeness check]}
\li{Clarity score: [evaluation]}
\li{Sentence variety: [evaluation]}
\li{Paragraph length: [evaluation]}
\li{\strong{Introduction}: [Specific improvements]}
\li{\strong{Body}: [Specific improvements]}
\li{\strong{Conclusion}: [Specific improvements]}
\li{\strong{Title}: [Options if needed]}
\li{[ ] All claims sourced}
\li{[ ] Citations formatted}
\li{[ ] Examples clear}
\li{[ ] Transitions smooth}
\li{[ ] Call to action present}
\li{[ ] Proofread for typos}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Examples}
\subtree{
\title{Example 1: Teresa Torres's Workflow}
\p{\strong{User}: "I'm writing an article about continuous discovery. Help me create an outline."}

\p{\strong{Process}:}

\ol{
\li{Collaborates on outline structure}
\li{Identifies research needs}
\li{User starts writing introduction}
\li{Reviews and improves the hook}
\li{User writes each section}
\li{Provides feedback after each section}
\li{Conducts research and adds citations}
\li{Final review of complete draft}
\li{Polish and prep for publishing}
}

\p{\strong{Result}: Well-researched, properly cited article written in Teresa's voice with strong structure and flow.}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example 2: Research-Heavy Article}
\p{\strong{User}: "I'm writing about AI's impact on product management. Help me find current data and examples."}

\p{\strong{Output}:}

\pre{\startverb
## Research Compiled

### Recent Data
- Gartner: 80% of PMs will use AI tools by 2025 [1]
- Survey: 45% report faster feature shipping [2]
- Case study: Airbnb's AI-assisted prioritization [3]

### Expert Quotes
- "AI amplifies PM judgment, not replaces it" - Marty Cagan
- [Additional quotes with citations]

### Real Examples
1. **Company A**: Used AI for user research synthesis
   - Result: 60% time savings
   - Source: [citation]

2. **Company B**: AI-powered roadmap analysis
   - Result: Better stakeholder alignment
   - Source: [citation]

All added to your outline with proper citations.
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example 3: Hook Improvement}
\p{\strong{User's Original Hook}: > "Product management is changing because of AI. In this article, I'll discuss some ways AI affects product managers."}

\p{\strong{Improved Options}:}

\p{\strong{Option 1 (Data-driven)}: > "Last month, I asked AI to analyze 500 customer interviews. It took 30 minutes instead of 3 weeks. Product management will never be the same."}

\p{\strong{Option 2 (Question)}: > "What if you could talk to every customer, read every review, and analyze every support ticket—all before your morning coffee?"}

\p{\strong{Option 3 (Story)}: > "Sarah spent two weeks building the wrong feature. Not because she didn't understand her users, but because she couldn't process the hundreds of interviews fast enough to spot the pattern."}
}

\subtree{
\title{Example 4: Section Feedback}
\p{\strong{User}: "Just finished my 'Common Mistakes' section. Thoughts?"}

\p{\strong{Response}:}

\pre{\startverb
# Feedback: Common Mistakes Section

## What Works Well ✓
- Strong examples (the Slack notification story)
- Clear structure (3 mistakes, clean layout)
- Practical advice for each mistake

## Suggestions

### Make It More Specific
Your second point says "Bad prioritization" but could be stronger:

Current:
> "Many teams prioritize badly by focusing on features instead of outcomes."

Suggested:
> "I've watched teams ship 14 features in a quarter yet move none of their key metrics. They prioritized activity over progress."

### Add Data
The third mistake would benefit from evidence:
> "[Add citation]: Studies show teams without regular user contact are 3x more likely to build unused features [needs source]"

### Flow Improvement
Consider reordering: Mistake 3 → Mistake 2 → Mistake 1
This builds from small to big impact.

Ready for the next section!
\stopverb}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Writing Workflows}
\subtree{
\title{Blog Post Workflow}
\ol{
\li{Outline together}
\li{Research key points}
\li{Write introduction → get feedback}
\li{Write body sections → feedback each}
\li{Write conclusion → final review}
\li{Polish and edit}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Newsletter Workflow}
\ol{
\li{Discuss hook ideas}
\li{Quick outline (shorter format)}
\li{Draft in one session}
\li{Review for clarity and links}
\li{Quick polish}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Technical Tutorial Workflow}
\ol{
\li{Outline steps}
\li{Write code examples}
\li{Add explanations}
\li{Test instructions}
\li{Add troubleshooting section}
\li{Final review for accuracy}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Thought Leadership Workflow}
\ol{
\li{Brainstorm unique angle}
\li{Research existing perspectives}
\li{Develop your thesis}
\li{Write with strong POV}
\li{Add supporting evidence}
\li{Craft compelling conclusion}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Pro Tips}
\ol{
\li{\strong{Work in VS Code}: Better than web Claude for long-form writing}
\li{\strong{One section at a time}: Get feedback incrementally}
\li{\strong{Save research separately}: Keep a research.md file}
\li{\strong{Version your drafts}: article-v1.md, article-v2.md, etc.}
\li{\strong{Read aloud}: Use feedback to identify clunky sentences}
\li{\strong{Set deadlines}: "I want to finish the draft today"}
\li{\strong{Take breaks}: Write, get feedback, pause, revise}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{File Organization}
\p{Recommended structure for writing projects:}

\pre{\startverb
~/writing/article-name/
├── outline.md          # Your outline
├── research.md         # All research and citations
├── draft-v1.md         # First draft
├── draft-v2.md         # Revised draft
├── final.md            # Publication-ready
├── feedback.md         # Collected feedback
└── sources/            # Reference materials
    ├── study1.pdf
    └── article2.md
\stopverb}
}

\subtree{
\title{Best Practices}
\subtree{
\title{For Research}
\ul{
\li{Verify sources before citing}
\li{Use recent data when possible}
\li{Balance different perspectives}
\li{Link to original sources}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{For Feedback}
\ul{
\li{Be specific about what you want: "Is this too technical?"}
\li{Share your concerns: "I'm worried this section drags"}
\li{Ask questions: "Does this flow logically?"}
\li{Request alternatives: "What's another way to explain this?"}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{For Voice}
\ul{
\li{Share examples of your writing}
\li{Specify tone preferences}
\li{Point out good matches: "That sounds like me!"}
\li{Flag mismatches: "Too formal for my style"}
}
}
}

\subtree{
\title{Related Use Cases}
\ul{
\li{Creating social media posts from articles}
\li{Adapting content for different audiences}
\li{Writing email newsletters}
\li{Drafting technical documentation}
\li{Creating presentation content}
\li{Writing case studies}
\li{Developing course outlines}
}
}
}